04347nam a22005655i 9780889208216DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892082167 a10.51644/97808892082162doi  a(DE-B1597)667360  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX9721.3 .E28 2006 7aREL1050002bisacsh04a287.961 aEason, Andrew Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen in God’s Army :bGender and Equality in the Early Salvation Army /cAndrew Mark Eason. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Women and Religion ;v700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tGender, Stratification and the Sacred -- tAn Ambiguous Heritage: The Salvation Army’s Victorian and Evangelical Roots -- tWilliam Booth and Women: Settled Views? -- tA Gendered Geography: Male Salvationists and Women -- tCatherine Booth: A Public and Domestic Legacy -- tPublic and Domestic Service: The Experiences of Female Officers -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tSeries Published by WilfridLaurierUniversity Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies inReligion/Corporation Canadienne des SciencesReligieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe early Salvation Army professed its commitment to sexual equality in ministry and leadership. In fact, its founding constitution proclaimed women had the right to preach and hold any office in the organization. But did they? Women in God’s Army is the first study of its kind devoted to the critical analysis of this central claim. It traces the extent to which this egalitarian ideal was realized in the private and public lives of first- and second-generation female Salvationists in Britain and argues that the Salvation Army was found wanting in its overall commitment to women’s equality with men. Bold pronouncements were not matched by actual practice in the home or in public ministry. Andrew Mark Eason traces the nature of these discrepancies, as well as the Victorian and evangelical factors that lay behind them. He demonstrates how Salvationists often assigned roles and responsibilities on the basis of gender rather than equality, and the ways in which these discriminatory practices were supported by a male-defined theology and authority. He views this story from a number of angles, including historical, gender and feminist theology, ensuring it will be of interest to a wide spectrum of readers. Salvationists themselves will appreciate the light it sheds on recent debates. Ultimately, however, anyone who wants to learn more about the human struggle for equality will find this book enlightening.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSexism in religionzGreat Britain. 0aWomen and religion. 4aHistory. 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920821640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208216/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles